{"word":"ἔρος","slug":"ἔρος","sections":[{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":""},{"paragraph":"<el><b>ἔρος1</b></el> <br/><b><a href='S:Etymology'>Etym.</a> </b><a href='S:poetically'>poet.</a> form of <a href='S:ἔρως'><el>ἔρως</el></a> (<a href='S:confer, compare'>cf.</a> <a href='S:γέλως'><el>γέλως</el></a>)\n<p/><div class='li500'><b>I. </b><i>love, desire</i>, <b><a href='S:Homer'>Hom.</a></b>, <a href='S:et cetera'>etc.</a><p/></div><div class='li500'><b>II. </b>as <a href='S:nominative'>nom.</a> pr. <i>Eros</i>, the god of love, <b><a href='S:Hesiod'>Hes.</a></b><p/></div> <hr/> <el><b>ἔρος2</b></el> <p/><i>wool</i>, only occurs in the ionic for <el>εἶρος.</el><p/>"}]}